a^2+b^2=c^2
(3)
c
 2\times\text{area} = \text{inradius}\times\text{perimeter} 
 2\times\text{area} = ab 
 \text{inradius}=a-1\quad\text{and}\quad\text{perimeter}=c^2 
 \begin{align} \overbrace{(a-1)}^{\text{inradius}}\overbrace{(a+b+c)}^{\text{perimeter}}&=ab\tag{1}\\ (a-1)(a+c)&=b\tag{2} \end{align} 
 \overbrace{a+b+c}^{\text{perimeter}}=c^2\tag{3} 
 \begin{align} (a-1)(a+c)&=c^2-c-a\tag{4}\\ a(a+c)&=c^2\tag{5}\\ \left(\frac ac\right)^2+\frac ac&=1\tag{6}\\ \frac ac&=\frac1\phi\tag{7} \end{align} 
 \begin{align} b^2&=ac\tag{8}\\ \left(\frac bc\right)^2&=\frac ac\tag{9}\\ \frac bc&=\frac1{\sqrt\phi}\tag{10} \end{align} 
 \begin{align} c &=\frac ac+\frac bc+1\tag{11}\\ &=\frac1\phi+\frac1{\sqrt\phi}+1\tag{12} \end{align} 
